Wash and dry produce.

Halve, core, and thinly slice @long green pepper{1} into strips. Quarter @lime{1}. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%oz}. Drain @pineapple{4%oz}.

Drizzle @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a hot #large pan{}. Add @pulled pork{8%oz}, green pepper, and @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}; cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until pork is warmed through and green pepper is slightly softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Add half the @Tex-Mex paste{1} (all for 4) and a splash of water; stir until mixture is combined and creates saucy pork. Remove from heat. (For 4, cook in batches, wiping out pan and adding a drizzle of oil between batches.)

> While the pork cooks, move on to the next steps.

Divide @guacamole{1/2%cup} between two #serving bowls{} (four serving bowls for 4). Stir in a squeeze of lime (big squeeze for 4), a pinch of cilantro, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

> You can plate chips and guac at this point!

In a #small microwave-safe bowl{}, mix drained pineapple, @sugar{1/4%tsp} (½ tsp for 4), and juice from one lime wedge (two wedges for 4). Microwave for ~{30%seconds}.

Drain any liquid from pineapple mixture and stir in @pico de gallo{4%oz}(drained) and a pinch of cilantro.

Wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{}; microwave for ~{30%seconds}.

Fill tortillas with pulled pork and pepper mixture. Using a #slotted spoon{}, top with pineapple salsa. Garnish with remaining cilantro and dollop with @sour cream{3%tbsp}. Drizzle with as much @hot sauce{2%tsp} as you like.

Serve tacos with @blue corn tortilla chips{3%oz}, cantina guacamole, and any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Pulled Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.